//When you divide one int by another int, Java gives you an int answer. The fractional part is completely thrown away not rounded. It just truncates. So 7 / 2 gives 3, not 3.5. The .5 is discarded. 5 / 3 gives 1.To avoid losing the fraction: Make at least one of the numbers a decimal type before dividing. If you divide a double by an int, or int by a double, the answer will be a double with decimals kept. You can do this by writing 7.0 / 2 or by casting: (double)7 / 2.
